can do this in seven minutes usually my introduction alone is seven minutes um so

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:19.620
these are my disclosures um so don't need to introduce this to this audience uh you know mds

00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:27.520
and aml are incredibly polyclonal diseases and for that reason we are very interested in this

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:32.560
polyclonality, especially at the level of stem cells and pre-leukemic stem cells in those diseases.

00:00:33.380 --> 00:00:38.760
And while we and others have focused very much on genetic heterogeneity and genetic markers

00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:44.980
mutations to define subclones, there's other mechanisms of heterogeneity. And one of those

00:00:44.980 --> 00:00:52.560
mechanisms is actually transcription itself. And what I want to point out here is that transcription

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:59.640
is actually very much a non-continuous process. And this is well known for a long time. We didn't

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:07.280
discover this. We didn't come up with this. So basically every gene expression locus that has

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:15.260
ever been studied shows that RNA transcription is not continuously occurring, but it occurs in

00:01:15.260 --> 00:01:21.960
short bursts. And you can see this. This is data from our lab on the P21 locus with the live cell

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:27.160
reporter assay in collaboration with Rob Coleman's lab. What you can see now in this area under the

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:33.080
curve is that there's really transcriptional bursts, these peaks, followed by periods of

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:38.260
silence. And this is really how gene expression works. Ultimately, transcription machinery,

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:44.720
transcription factors recruit one and exactly one molecule of polymerase 2. And then this one

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:50.160
molecule of polymerase 2 is synthesizing one molecule of RNA. And then, of course, you can

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.540
have multiple molecules and you can have a burst of.

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:57.040
You can have five RNAs, you can have four, you can have three, you can have 10, but it's a defined

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:03.480
number of RNA molecules that are synthesized. And then again, there is periods of silence. So

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:09.560
transcription is very much a bursty process. What does it mean? So a few years ago, we asked a very

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:15.020
fundamental question, and that is, is observed heterogeneity that we all find and describe in

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:21.260
our single-cell RNA-seq studies, are those really describing true subpopulation diversity? Or is

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:22.540
some of that simply driven by the fact that it's a single-cell RNA-seq study? And if so,

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:26.680
is that really driven by the biophysical stochasticity and the bursting of the transcriptional

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:32.860
process? And to do this, we used a methodology called single-molecule RNA fish. This was, again,

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:39.920
in collaboration with Rob Singers and Rob Coleman's lab. In the interest of time, I can't go into

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:45.680
technical details. We published this, took us a while to figure this out and to do this on primary

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:52.540
cells, but you really get very robust assays that really can detect on an image, on an image, on an

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:57.820
imaging basis, single molecules of RNA in a cell. Because it's imaging-based, you get a lot of

00:02:57.820 --> 00:03:02.620
information, accurate counts, you have subcellular localization, and you have the bursting

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:09.380
information. If you have more than one molecule in the nucleus in one spot, you know that's where

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:13.960
the bursts are occurring. And the only thing I want to point out here in the interest of time

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:21.640
is that we are able to, of course, detect all the well-expressed RNAs, but also, as you can see here

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:29.140
with hematopoietic subpopulations, we can reliably detect single digits of RNAs in the cell, so we're

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:35.040
seeing much more. It's a locus-based assay, so it's not genome-wide like RNA-seq, but we do see

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:42.500
transcripts that are well beyond the detection limit of what RNA-seq can do. Now, through live

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:49.080
cell imaging, we asked the question, are transcription states primed early in stem

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:52.540
cells, or are they still fluctuating, which is what we're trying to do. And we found that

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:59.300
we hypothesized, and so we did this live cell imaging and transcriptional assessment assay,

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:05.040
and what we found, I'll cut to the chase here in the interest of time, is that stem cells actually

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:11.640
are not locked into certain transcriptional pathways from the get-go, but that hematopoietic

00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:18.040
stem cells actually shuttle between transcription states, pretty much what we had thought would

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:22.540
happen if you think about the stochasticity of the process. This is here described,

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:29.120
for the fluctuation between PU1, a very important myeloid and lymphoid transcription factor, and

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:35.460
GATA, erythroid factors, and so really what you can see is that stem cells shuttle back and forth,

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:42.300
so the same cell, dependent on the time of the assay, looks differently transcriptionally at

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:47.760
different time points. And, you know, this is just visualizing this further, so you have cells

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:52.240
that fluctuate in and out of PU1 high or GATA high states,

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:58.880
at any given time point, you can detect, you know, if you want a transcriptional positioning,

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:04.080
that doesn't mean the cell is staying there and is locked into, let's say, a PU1 high state,

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:09.840
but it can come back, so there's a constant fluctuation, not just at the level of from

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:17.040
cell to cell, but within the same cell, so the time point of the assay matters, and snapshot assays

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:22.500
cannot reliably predict, you know, where the cell was before and where it will be in two hours,

00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:29.360
from now. Now, this is obviously very important, so we have now this amazing transcriptional plasticity,

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:35.520
and we now say, you know, we actually, we try to avoid the term "state" to some extent, and we more

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:43.680
describe it as a transcriptional space that cells and subclones actually occupy. Now, you ask, okay,

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:48.720
this is all fine, this is RNA, how about protein? And I hope this video plays, so we've also made

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:51.200
advances in the

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:57.360
visualization of single protein molecules of transcription factor. Again, this is work in

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:02.640
collaboration with Rock Coleman's lab, we use halo and snap-tagged proteins, and what you see

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:10.000
here in this video are single molecules of PU1 as they move around in the nucleus, and so really,

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:15.280
these are single transcription factor molecules that browse the genome, then you see some of them

00:06:15.280 --> 00:06:22.240
that actually sit there, and where you can visualize the, you know, where they are sitting, or that they are

